1
0:00:16.014,000 --> 0:00:19,000
I'm going to talk today about energy and climate.

2
0:00:20.363,000 --> 0:00:21,000
And that might seem a bit surprising,

3
0:00:22.165,000 --> 0:00:25,000
because my full-time work at the foundation

4
0:00:25.338,000 --> 0:00:27,000
is mostly about vaccines and seeds,

5
0:00:27.397,000 --> 0:00:3,000
about the things that we need to invent and deliver

6
0:00:30.989,000 --> 0:00:33,000
to help the poorest two billion live better lives.

7
0:00:35.741,000 --> 0:00:39,000
But energy and climate are extremely important to these people;

8
0:00:40.26,000 --> 0:00:44,000
in fact, more important than to anyone else on the planet.

9
0:00:45.053,000 --> 0:00:5,000
The climate getting worse means that many years, their crops won't grow:

10
0:00:50.788,000 --> 0:00:53,000
there will be too much rain, not enough rain;

11
0:00:53.843,000 --> 0:00:58,000
things will change in ways their fragile environment simply can't support.

12
0:00:59.804,000 --> 0:01:02,000
And that leads to starvation, it leads to uncertainty, it leads to unrest.

13
0:01:04.132,000 --> 0:01:07,000
So, the climate changes will be terrible for them.

14
0:01:08.093,000 --> 0:01:11,000
Also, the price of energy is very important to them.

15
0:01:11.26,000 --> 0:01:13,000
In fact, if you could pick just one thing

16
0:01:13.562,000 --> 0:01:17,000
to lower the price of to reduce poverty, by far you would pick energy.

17
0:01:18.962,000 --> 0:01:2,000
Now, the price of energy has come down over time.

18
0:01:22.343,000 --> 0:01:28,000
Really advanced civilization is based on advances in energy.

19
0:01:29.038,000 --> 0:01:32,000
The coal revolution fueled the Industrial Revolution,

20
0:01:32.633,000 --> 0:01:36,000
and, even in the 1900s, we've seen a very rapid decline

21
0:01:36.718,000 --> 0:01:37,000
in the price of electricity,

22
0:01:38.26,000 --> 0:01:41,000
and that's why we have refrigerators, air-conditioning;

23
0:01:41.666,000 --> 0:01:44,000
we can make modern materials and do so many things.

24
0:01:45.486,000 --> 0:01:51,000
And so, we're in a wonderful situation with electricity in the rich world.

25
0:01:52.544,000 --> 0:01:54,000
But as we make it cheaper -- and let's say,

26
0:01:55.447,000 --> 0:01:57,000
let's go for making it twice as cheap --

27
0:01:59.616,000 --> 0:02:,000
we need to meet a new constraint,

28
0:02:02.037,000 --> 0:02:05,000
and that constraint has to do with CO2.

29
0:02:06.003,000 --> 0:02:09,000
CO2 is warming the planet,

30
0:02:09.096,000 --> 0:02:14,000
and the equation on CO2 is actually a very straightforward one.

31
0:02:14.26,000 --> 0:02:17,000
If you sum up the CO2 that gets emitted,

32
0:02:18.866,000 --> 0:02:2,000
that leads to a temperature increase,

33
0:02:21.26,000 --> 0:02:24,000
and that temperature increase leads to some very negative effects:

34
0:02:25.26,000 --> 0:02:28,000
the effects on the weather; perhaps worse, the indirect effects,

35
0:02:29.197,000 --> 0:02:33,000
in that the natural ecosystems can't adjust to these rapid changes,

36
0:02:33.914,000 --> 0:02:35,000
and so you get ecosystem collapses.

37
0:02:36.66,000 --> 0:02:41,000
Now, the exact amount of how you map from a certain increase of CO2

38
0:02:42.079,000 --> 0:02:45,000
to what temperature will be, and where the positive feedbacks are --

39
0:02:45.393,000 --> 0:02:47,000
there's some uncertainty there, but not very much.

40
0:02:48.526,000 --> 0:02:51,000
And there's certainly uncertainty about how bad those effects will be,

41
0:02:51.85,000 --> 0:02:52,000
but they will be extremely bad.

42
0:02:54.461,000 --> 0:02:56,000
I asked the top scientists on this several times:

43
0:02:56.787,000 --> 0:02:58,000
Do we really have to get down to near zero?

44
0:02:59.335,000 --> 0:03:02,000
Can't we just cut it in half or a quarter?

45
0:03:02.392,000 --> 0:03:05,000
And the answer is, until we get near to zero,

46
0:03:06.26,000 --> 0:03:07,000
the temperature will continue to rise.

47
0:03:08.718,000 --> 0:03:09,000
And so that's a big challenge.

48
0:03:10.512,000 --> 0:03:12,000
It's very different than saying,

49
0:03:12.762,000 --> 0:03:15,000
"We're a twelve-foot-high truck trying to get under a ten-foot bridge,

50
0:03:16.122,000 --> 0:03:18,000
and we can just sort of squeeze under."

51
0:03:18.869,000 --> 0:03:2,000
This is something that has to get to zero.

52
0:03:22.828,000 --> 0:03:25,000
Now, we put out a lot of carbon dioxide every year --

53
0:03:26.121,000 --> 0:03:28,000
over 26 billion tons.

54
0:03:28.842,000 --> 0:03:31,000
For each American, it's about 20 tons.

55
0:03:32.438,000 --> 0:03:34,000
For people in poor countries, it's less than one ton.

56
0:03:35.26,000 --> 0:03:38,000
It's an average of about five tons for everyone on the planet.

57
0:03:39.402,000 --> 0:03:43,000
And somehow, we have to make changes that will bring that down to zero.

58
0:03:44.877,000 --> 0:03:46,000
It's been constantly going up.

59
0:03:47.045,000 --> 0:03:51,000
It's only various economic changes that have even flattened it at all,

60
0:03:51.674,000 --> 0:03:54,000
so we have to go from rapidly rising to falling,

61
0:03:55.155,000 --> 0:03:57,000
and falling all the way to zero.

62
0:03:57.261,000 --> 0:04:,000
This equation has four factors, a little bit of multiplication.

63
0:04:01.26,000 --> 0:04:04,000
So you've got a thing on the left, CO2, that you want to get to zero,

64
0:04:05.048,000 --> 0:04:08,000
and that's going to be based on the number of people,

65
0:04:08.462,000 --> 0:04:11,000
the services each person is using on average,

66
0:04:11.876,000 --> 0:04:13,000
the energy, on average, for each service,

67
0:04:14.769,000 --> 0:04:17,000
and the CO2 being put out per unit of energy.

68
0:04:18.992,000 --> 0:04:19,000
So let's look at each one of these,

69
0:04:20.969,000 --> 0:04:22,000
and see how we can get this down to zero.

70
0:04:24.498,000 --> 0:04:27,000
Probably, one of these numbers is going to have to get pretty near to zero.

71
0:04:28.074,000 --> 0:04:29,000
(Laughter)

72
0:04:29.28,000 --> 0:04:3,000
That's back from high school algebra.

73
0:04:31.278,000 --> 0:04:32,000
But let's take a look.

74
0:04:32.958,000 --> 0:04:33,000
First, we've got population.

75
0:04:35.454,000 --> 0:04:37,000
The world today has 6.8 billion people.

76
0:04:38.26,000 --> 0:04:4,000
That's headed up to about nine billion.

77
0:04:40.487,000 --> 0:04:44,000
Now, if we do a really great job on new vaccines,

78
0:04:44.572,000 --> 0:04:46,000
health care, reproductive health services,

79
0:04:47.053,000 --> 0:04:5,000
we could lower that by, perhaps, 10 or 15 percent.

80
0:04:50.178,000 --> 0:04:53,000
But there, we see an increase of about 1.3.

81
0:04:54.685,000 --> 0:04:56,000
The second factor is the services we use.

82
0:04:57.715,000 --> 0:04:58,000
This encompasses everything:

83
0:04:59.504,000 --> 0:05:03,000
the food we eat, clothing, TV, heating.

84
0:05:04.037,000 --> 0:05:05,000
These are very good things.

85
0:05:06.189,000 --> 0:05:09,000
Getting rid of poverty means providing these services

86
0:05:09.92,000 --> 0:05:11,000
to almost everyone on the planet.

87
0:05:11.949,000 --> 0:05:14,000
And it's a great thing for this number to go up.

88
0:05:15.26,000 --> 0:05:17,000
In the rich world, perhaps the top one billion,

89
0:05:17.523,000 --> 0:05:19,000
we probably could cut back and use less,

90
0:05:19.932,000 --> 0:05:23,000
but every year, this number, on average, is going to go up,

91
0:05:24.072,000 --> 0:05:27,000
and so, overall, that will more than double

92
0:05:27.26,000 --> 0:05:29,000
the services delivered per person.

93
0:05:30.398,000 --> 0:05:32,000
Here we have a very basic service:

94
0:05:32.525,000 --> 0:05:35,000
Do you have lighting in your house to be able to read your homework?

95
0:05:35.961,000 --> 0:05:36,000
And, in fact, these kids don't,

96
0:05:37.504,000 --> 0:05:39,000
so they're going out and reading their schoolwork

97
0:05:39.846,000 --> 0:05:4,000
under the street lamps.

98
0:05:42.538,000 --> 0:05:45,000
Now, efficiency, "E," the energy for each service --

99
0:05:46.26,000 --> 0:05:47,000
here, finally we have some good news.

100
0:05:48.261,000 --> 0:05:49,000
We have something that's not going up.

101
0:05:50.147,000 --> 0:05:53,000
Through various inventions and new ways of doing lighting,

102
0:05:53.26,000 --> 0:05:58,000
through different types of cars, different ways of building buildings --

103
0:05:58.715,000 --> 0:05:59,000
there are a lot of services

104
0:06:00.374,000 --> 0:06:03,000
where you can bring the energy for that service down

105
0:06:03.738,000 --> 0:06:04,000
quite substantially.

106
0:06:05.26,000 --> 0:06:08,000
Some individual services even bring it down by 90 percent.

107
0:06:08.779,000 --> 0:06:11,000
There are other services, like how we make fertilizer,

108
0:06:12.149,000 --> 0:06:13,000
or how we do air transport,

109
0:06:13.815,000 --> 0:06:15,000
where the rooms for improvement are far, far less.

110
0:06:17.156,000 --> 0:06:21,000
And so overall, if we're optimistic, we may get a reduction

111
0:06:21.478,000 --> 0:06:25,000
of a factor of three to even, perhaps, a factor of six.

112
0:06:26.868,000 --> 0:06:28,000
But for these first three factors now,

113
0:06:29.26,000 --> 0:06:34,000
we've gone from 26 billion to, at best, maybe 13 billion tons,

114
0:06:34.344,000 --> 0:06:35,000
and that just won't cut it.

115
0:06:36.259,000 --> 0:06:39,000
So let's look at this fourth factor -- this is going to be a key one --

116
0:06:40.081,000 --> 0:06:45,000
and this is the amount of CO2 put out per each unit of energy.

117
0:06:46.434,000 --> 0:06:49,000
So the question is: Can you actually get that to zero?

118
0:06:49.983,000 --> 0:06:51,000
If you burn coal, no.

119
0:06:52.913,000 --> 0:06:53,000
If you burn natural gas, no.

120
0:06:54.412,000 --> 0:06:57,000
Almost every way we make electricity today,

121
0:06:57.539,000 --> 0:07:02,000
except for the emerging renewables and nuclear, puts out CO2.

122
0:07:03.551,000 --> 0:07:06,000
And so, what we're going to have to do at a global scale,

123
0:07:06.828,000 --> 0:07:07,000
is create a new system.

124
0:07:09.133,000 --> 0:07:1,000
So we need energy miracles.

125
0:07:11.786,000 --> 0:07:15,000
Now, when I use the term "miracle," I don't mean something that's impossible.

126
0:07:16.103,000 --> 0:07:18,000
The microprocessor is a miracle.

127
0:07:18.547,000 --> 0:07:19,000
The personal computer is a miracle.

128
0:07:20.556,000 --> 0:07:22,000
The Internet and its services are a miracle.

129
0:07:23.047,000 --> 0:07:27,000
So the people here have participated in the creation of many miracles.

130
0:07:28.117,000 --> 0:07:29,000
Usually, we don't have a deadline

131
0:07:30.118,000 --> 0:07:32,000
where you have to get the miracle by a certain date.

132
0:07:32.62,000 --> 0:07:35,000
Usually, you just kind of stand by, and some come along, some don't.

133
0:07:36.625,000 --> 0:07:4,000
This is a case where we actually have to drive at full speed

134
0:07:40.748,000 --> 0:07:43,000
and get a miracle in a pretty tight timeline.

135
0:07:45.749,000 --> 0:07:47,000
Now, I thought, "How could I really capture this?

136
0:07:48.718,000 --> 0:07:5,000
Is there some kind of natural illustration,

137
0:07:50.965,000 --> 0:07:53,000
some demonstration that would grab people's imagination here?"

138
0:07:55.502,000 --> 0:07:58,000
I thought back to a year ago when I brought mosquitoes,

139
0:07:59.26,000 --> 0:08:01,000
and somehow people enjoyed that.

140
0:08:01.914,000 --> 0:08:02,000
(Laughter)

141
0:08:03.545,000 --> 0:08:07,000
It really got them involved in the idea of, you know,

142
0:08:07.615,000 --> 0:08:09,000
there are people who live with mosquitoes.

143
0:08:09.691,000 --> 0:08:12,000
With energy, all I could come up with is this.

144
0:08:14.101,000 --> 0:08:17,000
I decided that releasing fireflies

145
0:08:17.259,000 --> 0:08:2,000
would be my contribution to the environment here this year.

146
0:08:21.376,000 --> 0:08:23,000
So here we have some natural fireflies.

147
0:08:24.26,000 --> 0:08:27,000
I'm told they don't bite; in fact, they might not even leave that jar.

148
0:08:27.893,000 --> 0:08:28,000
(Laughter)

149
0:08:31.093,000 --> 0:08:35,000
Now, there's all sorts of gimmicky solutions like that one,

150
0:08:35.255,000 --> 0:08:36,000
but they don't really add up to much.

151
0:08:37.18,000 --> 0:08:41,000
We need solutions, either one or several,

152
0:08:41.227,000 --> 0:08:46,000
that have unbelievable scale and unbelievable reliability.

153
0:08:47.268,000 --> 0:08:5,000
And although there's many directions that people are seeking,

154
0:08:50.76,000 --> 0:08:53,000
I really only see five that can achieve the big numbers.

155
0:08:54.861,000 --> 0:08:58,000
I've left out tide, geothermal, fusion, biofuels.

156
0:08:59.172,000 --> 0:09:,000
Those may make some contribution,

157
0:09:01.173,000 --> 0:09:03,000
and if they can do better than I expect, so much the better.

158
0:09:04.046,000 --> 0:09:07,000
But my key point here is that we're going to have to work on

159
0:09:07.992,000 --> 0:09:08,000
each of these five,

160
0:09:09.742,000 --> 0:09:12,000
and we can't give up any of them because they look daunting,

161
0:09:13.563,000 --> 0:09:15,000
because they all have significant challenges.

162
0:09:17.061,000 --> 0:09:19,000
Let's look first at burning fossil fuels,

163
0:09:19.705,000 --> 0:09:21,000
either burning coal or burning natural gas.

164
0:09:23.021,000 --> 0:09:27,000
What you need to do there seems like it might be simple, but it's not.

165
0:09:27.131,000 --> 0:09:29,000
And that's to take all the CO2,

166
0:09:29.588,000 --> 0:09:31,000
after you've burned it, going out the flue,

167
0:09:32.26,000 --> 0:09:35,000
pressurize it, create a liquid, put it somewhere,

168
0:09:35.429,000 --> 0:09:36,000
and hope it stays there.

169
0:09:37.452,000 --> 0:09:38,000
Now, we have some pilot things

170
0:09:39.098,000 --> 0:09:41,000
that do this at the 60 to 80 percent level.

171
0:09:41.461,000 --> 0:09:45,000
But getting up to that full percentage -- that will be very tricky.

172
0:09:45.884,000 --> 0:09:5,000
And agreeing on where these CO2 quantities should be put will be hard,

173
0:09:51.48,000 --> 0:09:53,000
but the toughest one here is this long-term issue:

174
0:09:54.166,000 --> 0:09:55,000
Who's going to be sure?

175
0:09:55.73,000 --> 0:09:56,000
Who's going to guarantee

176
0:09:57.352,000 --> 0:10:,000
something that is literally billions of times larger

177
0:10:00.445,000 --> 0:10:04,000
than any type of waste you think of in terms of nuclear or other things?

178
0:10:04.615,000 --> 0:10:06,000
This is a lot of volume.

179
0:10:07.694,000 --> 0:10:08,000
So that's a tough one.

180
0:10:09.527,000 --> 0:10:1,000
Next would be nuclear.

181
0:10:11.26,000 --> 0:10:13,000
It also has three big problems:

182
0:10:14.26,000 --> 0:10:17,000
cost, particularly in highly regulated countries, is high;

183
0:10:18.26,000 --> 0:10:22,000
the issue of safety, really feeling good about nothing could go wrong,

184
0:10:22.938,000 --> 0:10:25,000
that, even though you have these human operators,

185
0:10:25.966,000 --> 0:10:27,000
the fuel doesn't get used for weapons.

186
0:10:28.716,000 --> 0:10:29,000
And then what do you do with the waste?

187
0:10:30.695,000 --> 0:10:33,000
Although it's not very large, there are a lot of concerns about that.

188
0:10:34.123,000 --> 0:10:35,000
People need to feel good about it.

189
0:10:35.812,000 --> 0:10:39,000
So three very tough problems that might be solvable,

190
0:10:40.26,000 --> 0:10:41,000
and so, should be worked on.

191
0:10:42.449,000 --> 0:10:44,000
The last three of the five, I've grouped together.

192
0:10:45.164,000 --> 0:10:48,000
These are what people often refer to as the renewable sources.

193
0:10:49.101,000 --> 0:10:53,000
And they actually -- although it's great they don't require fuel --

194
0:10:53.148,000 --> 0:10:54,000
they have some disadvantages.

195
0:10:55.577,000 --> 0:11:,000
One is that the density of energy gathered in these technologies

196
0:11:01.443,000 --> 0:11:03,000
is dramatically less than a power plant.

197
0:11:03.53,000 --> 0:11:04,000
This is energy farming,

198
0:11:05.236,000 --> 0:11:09,000
so you're talking about many square miles, thousands of times more area

199
0:11:09.381,000 --> 0:11:11,000
than you think of as a normal energy plant.

200
0:11:12.758,000 --> 0:11:14,000
Also, these are intermittent sources.

201
0:11:15.37,000 --> 0:11:18,000
The sun doesn't shine all day, it doesn't shine every day,

202
0:11:18.809,000 --> 0:11:2,000
and likewise, the wind doesn't blow all the time.

203
0:11:21.26,000 --> 0:11:23,000
And so, if you depend on these sources,

204
0:11:23.673,000 --> 0:11:25,000
you have to have some way of getting the energy

205
0:11:26.047,000 --> 0:11:28,000
during those time periods that it's not available.

206
0:11:29.418,000 --> 0:11:31,000
So we've got big cost challenges here.

207
0:11:32.498,000 --> 0:11:33,000
We have transmission challenges;

208
0:11:34.42,000 --> 0:11:37,000
for example, say this energy source is outside your country,

209
0:11:38.008,000 --> 0:11:4,000
you not only need the technology,

210
0:11:40.125,000 --> 0:11:44,000
but you have to deal with the risk of the energy coming from elsewhere.

211
0:11:44.522,000 --> 0:11:45,000
And, finally, this storage problem.

212
0:11:47.06,000 --> 0:11:48,000
To dimensionalize this,

213
0:11:48.585,000 --> 0:11:51,000
I went through and looked at all the types of batteries made --

214
0:11:52.162,000 --> 0:11:56,000
for cars, for computers, for phones, for flashlights, for everything --

215
0:11:56.698,000 --> 0:12:,000
and compared that to the amount of electrical energy the world uses.

216
0:12:01.644,000 --> 0:12:04,000
What I found is that all the batteries we make now

217
0:12:05.261,000 --> 0:12:08,000
could store less than 10 minutes of all the energy.

218
0:12:09.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
And so, in fact, we need a big breakthrough here,

219
0:12:12.652,000 --> 0:12:15,000
something that's going to be a factor of 100 better

220
0:12:16.544,000 --> 0:12:17,000
than the approaches we have now.

221
0:12:18.401,000 --> 0:12:21,000
It's not impossible, but it's not a very easy thing.

222
0:12:22.594,000 --> 0:12:25,000
Now, this shows up when you try to get the intermittent source

223
0:12:26.26,000 --> 0:12:3,000
to be above, say, 20 to 30 percent of what you're using.

224
0:12:30.436,000 --> 0:12:32,000
If you're counting on it for 100 percent,

225
0:12:33.054,000 --> 0:12:36,000
you need an incredible miracle battery.

226
0:12:38.26,000 --> 0:12:41,000
Now, how are we going to go forward on this -- what's the right approach?

227
0:12:41.901,000 --> 0:12:44,000
Is it a Manhattan Project? What's the thing that can get us there?

228
0:12:45.504,000 --> 0:12:49,000
Well, we need lots of companies working on this -- hundreds.

229
0:12:50.339,000 --> 0:12:53,000
In each of these five paths, we need at least a hundred people.

230
0:12:53.942,000 --> 0:12:55,000
A lot of them, you'll look at and say, "They're crazy."

231
0:12:56.676,000 --> 0:12:57,000
That's good.

232
0:12:57.881,000 --> 0:12:59,000
And, I think, here in the TED group,

233
0:13:00.835,000 --> 0:13:03,000
we have many people who are already pursuing this.

234
0:13:04.816,000 --> 0:13:07,000
Bill Gross has several companies, including one called eSolar

235
0:13:08.26,000 --> 0:13:1,000
that has some great solar thermal technologies.

